- cocos2d-x version: 3.10

I only noticed because the `ProgressTo` Action wasn't doing anything (because of a [cast](https://github.com/cocos2d/cocos2d-x/blob/v3/cocos/2d/CCActionProgressTimer.cpp#L80)) when I set it to run on a `ui::LoadingBar`. 

Is it worth changing the `ui` nodes to all use the `setPercentage` style, and which allows the Action to be run on both, and clears up any confusion between both, or should I change `ProgressTo` to use a dynamic cast instead of a C style cast and check to make sure it's being run on a `ProgressTimer` and throw a warning if it's not?

On my own local fork of cocos, I check the dynamic cast, but I'm not sure this is good enough for the actual repo

```
    ui::LoadingBar* loading_bar = dynamic_cast<ui::LoadingBar*>(_target);
    if (loading_bar){
        loading_bar->setPercent(_from + (_to - _from) * time);
    } else {
        static_cast<ProgressTimer*>(_target)->setPercentage(_from + (_to - _from) * time);
    };

```

Maybe it's not worth doing anything and instead adding documentation somewhere not to use `ProgressTo` with anything in the `ui` namespace?

